TypeScript is a superset of JavaScript that adds static typing and other features to the language. It is designed to help developers catch errors early and improve code maintainability, thus making it a popular choice for large and complex applications.

Duck typing is a concept in object-oriented programming that refers to the idea that an object's type is determined by the properties it has, rather than by its class or interface. In other words, if an object has the same properties as another object, it is considered to be of the same type as that object, even if it is of a different class or interface.

In TypeScript, duck typing is supported through the use of type assertions. A type assertion is a way to tell TypeScript that you know better than it does what the type of a variable should be. For example, you might use a type assertion to tell TypeScript that a variable of type any should be treated as a type that you have defined.

